  "signature": "ed25519:b7e3f2a1c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d1e2f3a4b5c6d7e8f9a0b1c2d3e4f5a6b7c8d9e0f1",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "SQA plan must demonstrate version-controlled source with traceability to requirements, automated regression suite covering >90% of solver code paths, and independent third-party audit of the hemolysis sub-model. Gradation 4 requires formal documented test plans with sign-off.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver used for hemolysis prediction (OpenFOAM 8 with custom hemolysis transport model) has a version-controlled repository and automated regression tests covering core hydrodynamic solvers. However, the hemolysis sub-model (power-law Giersiepen-Wurzinger formulation) has not undergone independent third-party audit, and the regression suite covers only 61% of hemolysis-specific code paths. SQA documentation is incomplete relative to MRL 5 requirements. Achieved Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification must include method of manufactured solutions (MMS) for all governing equations including hemolysis transport, with observed order of accuracy within 10% of formal order. Gradation 4 requires MMS coverage of coupled momentum-hemolysis system.",
      "rationale": "MMS verification was performed for the Navier-Stokes solver and confirmed second-order spatial accuracy (observed order 1.94 vs. formal order 2.0). MMS was not extended to the hemolysis transport equation, which relies on a post-processing Lagrangian particle tracking approach. The particle tracking integration scheme was verified only through comparison to analytical streamline solutions in simple geometries, not through MMS. This gap prevents achievement of Gradation 4 for code verification."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence must be demonstrated using at least three systematically refined meshes with GCI < 2% on hemolysis index QoI. Gradation 4 requires Richardson extrapolation applied directly to hemolysis index with uncertainty bounds reported.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted with mesh sizes of 2.1M, 8.4M, and 33.6M cells (refinement ratio r=2). GCI for pressure head was 0.8%, meeting Gradation 4 requirements for hydrodynamic QoIs. However, GCI computed on the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) was 4.3% between the medium and fine meshes, exceeding the Gradation 4 threshold. Richardson extrapolation was applied to NIH but the extrapolated value differed from the fine-mesh result by 6.1%, indicating the asymptotic range had not been fully achieved for the hemolysis QoI. Achieved Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must match COU operating envelope within stated uncertainty bounds. Blood analog rheology, temperature, and inlet flow waveform must be documented and compared to clinical VAD operating conditions. Gradation 3 requires quantitative comparison of all boundary conditions.",
      "rationale": "Experimental validation data were collected using a glycerol-water blood analog at matched viscosity (3.5 mPa·s) and density. Temperature was controlled to 37°C ±0.5°C. However, the experimental inlet flow conditions used a steady-flow protocol, whereas clinical VAD operation involves pulsatile flow with cardiac cycle variation. This mismatch between steady experimental conditions and pulsatile COU conditions represents a test condition gap. Inlet turbulence intensity was not characterized experimentally. Achieved Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison of model predictions to experimental hemolysis measurements must include validation metric (e.g., E_rel or U_95) with explicit uncertainty decomposition separating experimental, numerical, and input uncertainty contributions. Gradation 4 requires area validation metric or equivalent with statistical significance testing.",
      "rationale": "Hemolysis index predictions were compared to experimental measurements at 5 operating points. Mean relative error across operating points was 18.3%, with individual point errors ranging from 9.1% to 31.7%. No formal validation metric (U_95, E_rel with uncertainty bars, or area metric) was computed. Experimental measurement uncertainty was reported as ±12% but was not propagated through the comparison. The comparison was presented graphically without statistical significance testing. This level of comparison supports Gradation 2 (qualitative trend agreement with quantitative error reporting) but not Gradation 4."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoI used in validation (NIH in modified Lagrangian power-law formulation) must be demonstrated to be the same quantity — or a rigorously justified surrogate — for the clinical hemolysis endpoint. Gradation 5 requires direct linkage to clinical hemolysis threshold with sensitivity analysis showing QoI is not a misleading surrogate.",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) is a widely used surrogate for clinical hemolysis in computational studies, but its relationship to in-vivo hemolysis in VAD patients is mediated by numerous physiological factors not captured in the CFD model (e.g., sub-hemolytic cumulative damage, platelet activation, patient hematocrit variability). The validation QoI (NIH computed from in-vitro steady-flow experiments) differs from the clinical QoI (plasma-free hemoglobin elevation in VAD patients) in both measurement context and mechanistic pathway. A sensitivity analysis was performed showing that NIH predictions are sensitive to the power-law exponents (α, β) in the hemolysis model, but no analysis was performed linking NIH uncertainty to clinical hemolysis threshold exceedance probability. Achieved Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "This factor governs the degree to which the validation activities — in-vitro hemolysis measurements on the FDA generic centrifugal pump using a glycerol-water blood analog under steady-flow conditions — are representative of the intended COU, which involves a Class III VAD operating in pulsatile physiological conditions within a patient. The validation geometry (FDA generic pump) is not the same device as any specific clinical VAD, though it is intended as a representative benchmark. The blood analog used (glycerol-water) replicates bulk viscosity but does not replicate red blood cell deformability, aggregation behavior, or the viscoelastic response that influences hemolysis at high shear rates. Steady-flow experimental conditions do not capture pulsatile hemodynamic loading that characterizes VAD operation. The validation operating points (3 flow rates × 2 rotational speeds = 6 conditions) cover a portion of the intended COU envelope (5 flow-speed combinations) but do not span the full range of clinical operating conditions, particularly at the extremes of the intended operating envelope where hemolysis risk is greatest. Taken together, these gaps in geometric similarity, fluid analog fidelity, flow condition representativeness, and operating point coverage collectively limit the relevance of the validation activities to the COU. The assessment team has carefully reviewed the available experimental literature and concludes that the existing validation evidence, while the most comprehensive available for this class of device, supports a Gradation 3 assessment: the validation activities are partially relevant to the COU with documented and quantified gaps, but do not achieve the full representativeness required for Gradation 5 at Model Risk Level 5. The team notes that the FDA benchmark dataset represents the current state of the art for centrifugal pump hemolysis validation, and that achieving Gradation 5 would require patient-specific in-vivo validation data that are not ethically or practically obtainable at the pre-market stage. This epistemic limitation is acknowledged as an irreducible gap in the current assessment cycle. The required level of 5 reflects the MRL 5 classification and the HIGH decision consequence; the gap between required (5) and achieved (3) is the primary driver of the Not Accepted decision for this COU."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated with residuals reduced by at least 6 orders of magnitude for all transport equations, and solution must be shown to be independent of solver tolerance settings. Gradation 3 requires documented convergence study across tolerance levels.",
      "rationale": "Solver convergence was monitored via residual reduction for continuity (5 orders), momentum (6 orders), and k-omega turbulence equations (4 orders). The hemolysis transport equation residuals were not monitored separately as it is solved in post-processing. No solver tolerance sensitivity study was performed. Factor flagged as not-assessed for the hemolysis transport component."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "User qualification records, simulation execution checklists, and independent peer review of simulation setup must be documented. Gradation 3 requires evidence that a second qualified analyst independently verified the simulation setup and boundary condition inputs.",
      "rationale": "No formal use error assessment was conducted. Simulation was set up and executed by a single analyst. No independent verification of boundary condition inputs, mesh setup, or hemolysis model parameter selection was performed. This represents an epistemic gap flagged at MRL 5. Factor not-assessed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form uncertainty must be quantified by comparing predictions from at least two physically distinct hemolysis model formulations (e.g., Giersiepen-Wurzinger vs. Taskin et al.) and demonstrating that the chosen model form does not introduce systematic bias exceeding the validation tolerance. Gradation 4 requires sensitivity analysis across model form alternatives with uncertainty bounds.",
      "rationale": "Only the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model was implemented and evaluated. No alternative model forms (Taskin, Arora, or mechanistic membrane pore models) were assessed. Model form uncertainty is therefore unquantified. This is a significant epistemic gap at MRL 5 given the known sensitivity of hemolysis predictions to model form selection. Factor not-assessed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model input parameters must be characterized with probability distributions derived from experimental measurement or literature meta-analysis. Monte Carlo UQ must propagate input uncertainty to hemolysis QoI with convergence demonstrated at N≥10,000 samples. Gradation 4 requires global sensitivity analysis (e.g., Sobol indices) identifying dominant input uncertainty contributors.",
      "rationale": "Monte Carlo UQ was performed with N=5,000 samples propagating uncertainty in blood viscosity (±8%), pump rotational speed (±0.5%), and hemolysis model exponents α and β (±15% based on literature range). Convergence of the Monte Carlo estimate was assessed at N=1,000, 2,000, and 5,000 samples; the 95th percentile NIH estimate changed by 3.2% between N=2,000 and N=5,000, suggesting marginal convergence. Global sensitivity analysis (Sobol indices) was not performed; only one-at-a-time sensitivity was assessed. The dominant uncertainty contributor (hemolysis model exponents) was identified qualitatively but not quantified via Sobol decomposition. Achieved Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental samples used for validation must be characterized for hematocrit, red blood cell age distribution, and storage conditions. Gradation 3 requires traceability of blood or blood analog samples to documented preparation protocols with inter-batch variability quantified.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used a glycerol-water analog; no biological blood samples were used. Inter-batch variability of the glycerol-water analog was not characterized. Sample preparation protocol was referenced to a published standard but batch-specific characterization data were not available. Factor not-assessed at the required Gradation 3 level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Equivalency between experimental input parameters (boundary conditions, fluid properties, geometry) and COU input parameters must be formally demonstrated through dimensionless parameter matching or justified scaling arguments. Gradation 3 requires quantitative equivalency table with uncertainty bounds on all input parameters.",
      "rationale": "A qualitative equivalency assessment was performed comparing experimental and COU input parameters. Reynolds number matching was achieved at 3 of 5 operating points. Womersley number matching was not possible due to the steady-flow experimental protocol. No formal equivalency table with uncertainty bounds was produced. Factor not-assessed at the required Gradation 3 level."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou2-vad-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Following review of all 13 credibility factors assessed under ASME V&V 40-2018 at Model Risk Level 5, the assessment team finds that the overall credibility evidence package is insufficient to support the intended COU. Seven factors were formally assessed; all seven achieved levels below their required levels. Six factors remain not-assessed, representing epistemic gaps that cannot be resolved without additional experimental and analytical work. The most critical gap is in Relevance of the validation activities to the COU (required: 5, achieved: 3), which reflects the fundamental limitation that in-vitro steady-flow validation on the FDA generic pump cannot be directly extrapolated to pulsatile VAD operation in Class III patients. The Monte Carlo UQ effort is acknowledged as a positive contribution but does not compensate for model form uncertainty (not quantified) and use error (not assessed). The decision is Not Accepted pending: (1) extension of validation to pulsatile flow conditions, (2) model form sensitivity analysis across at least two hemolysis formulations, (3) independent analyst verification of simulation setup, and (4) completion of Sobol global sensitivity analysis for model inputs.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
